    a: 0,
    r: "Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) presents with Kussmaul respirations (deep, rapid breathing as compensation for metabolic acidosis), a fruity or acetone breath odor from ketone production, and significantly elevated blood glucose (typically above 14 mmol/L). DKA involves hyperglycemia, not normal or low blood sugar. Shallow or slow breathing would indicate inadequate compensation. Normal glucose levels rule out DKA.",
